The paper deals with fundamental problems in computational geometry, such as point location, convex hull, Voronoi diagrams, and triangulation. These are all topics that fall under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also discusses algorithms and data structures, which are typically studied in the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The use of randomized algorithms and analysis of running time suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper's focus on manipulating information and avoiding online problems may make it relevant to the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the use of numerical methods and analysis of errors may make the paper relevant to the sub-category of numerical analysis (cs.NA).
